HEADWORD: Lineament
<hw>Lin"e*a*ment</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧n"⟦esl⟧*⟦adot⟧*m⟦eit⟧nt)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>lineamentum</ets>, fr. <ets>linea</ets>
line: cf. F. <ets>lin⟦eacute⟧ament</ets>. See 3d <er>Line</er>.]</ety>
<def>One of the outlines, exterior features, or distinctive marks, of a
body or figure, particularly of the face; feature; form; mark; --
usually in the <xex>plural</xex>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>lineaments</xex>
of the body.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Locke.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Lineaments</xex> in the
character.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Swift.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Man he seems⟦br⟧
In all his <qex>lineaments</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Linear</ent>⟦br⟧
